# .cursorrules — FieldCheck AI Checklist App
# Stack: Ruby on Rails (API) + React (Frontend)
# Domain: Contractor field tools, inspired by CompanyCam

---

## PROJECT CONTEXT

You are building **FieldCheck**, an AI-powered checklist app for contractors
(roofers, HVAC techs, plumbers, electricians, etc.).

Users are field workers — hands dirty, gloves on, standing on roofs. They
complete checklists using voice and photos, not typing. The AI does the matching.

Always keep this user in mind: **a roofer with dirty gloves, one thumb free,
on a ladder, with spotty LTE.** Every design decision flows from that image.

---

## TECH STACK

### Backend (Ruby on Rails)
- Rails 7.x API-only mode (`--api`)
- PostgreSQL database
- Devise for authentication (simple email/password)
- ActiveStorage for photo uploads (S3 in production, disk in dev)
- Sidekiq for background jobs
- RSpec + FactoryBot for testing

### Frontend (React)
- React 18 with hooks
- React Router v6 for routing
- Tailwind CSS for styling
- Zustand for global state management
- React Query (TanStack) for server state / caching
- Axios for HTTP
- Vite for bundling

### AI / External APIs
- **Claude API** (`claude-sonnet-4-20250514`) — voice intent matching, photo analysis, Q&A
- **OpenAI Whisper API** — speech-to-text transcription
- All AI calls go through the Rails backend — never call AI APIs directly from frontend

---

## RAILS CONVENTIONS

### API Structure
- All endpoints under `/api/v1/`
- Return JSON always. Use `render json:` not views
- Use serializers (ActiveModel::Serializers or fast_jsonapi pattern)
- Standard response envelope:
  ```json
  { "data": {...}, "meta": {}, "errors": [] }
  ```
- HTTP status codes must be explicit: `render json: ..., status: :created`

### Models
- Use UUIDs as primary keys (`id: :uuid`)
- Always add database indexes for foreign keys and frequently queried columns
- Enums defined in the model with string backing in DB:
  ```ruby
  enum trade_type: { roofing: 'roofing', hvac: 'hvac', ... }, _prefix: true
  ```
- Validations on model, not just controller
- No business logic in controllers — use service objects in `app/services/`

### Controllers
- Thin controllers. Extract logic to service objects
- Use `before_action` for auth and record finding
- Never return raw ActiveRecord errors — format them:
  ```ruby
  render json: { errors: resource.errors.full_messages }, status: :unprocessable_entity
  ```

### Service Objects
- One file per service in `app/services/`
- Named as verb + noun: `VoiceMatchService`, `PhotoAnalysisService`, `AiQaService`
- Single public method: `#call`
- Return a result object with `success?`, `data`, `error`
- Example pattern:
  ```ruby
  class VoiceMatchService
    def initialize(transcription:, items:)
      @transcription = transcription
      @items = items
    end

    def call
      # Claude API call here
      # Return structured result
    end

    private
    # helper methods
  end
  ```

### AI Service Rules
- All Claude API calls in `app/services/ai/`
- Always rescue from API errors and return graceful error result
- Log all AI calls with: input tokens, output tokens, latency, model used
- Never put prompts inline in controllers — define them as private methods or constants in service
- Confidence scores must be 0.0–1.0 floats, validated before use

### Testing
- Test all service objects with RSpec unit tests
- Test all API endpoints with request specs
- Use VCR cassettes for external API calls in tests
- Test AI confidence thresholds explicitly (mock different confidence values)
- Minimum 80% test coverage

---

## REACT CONVENTIONS

### Component Structure
```
src/
├── components/        # Reusable UI components
│   ├── ui/            # Primitives: Button, Card, Badge, etc.
│   ├── checklist/     # Checklist-specific components
│   ├── ai/            # AI action bar, voice UI, photo UI
│   └── project/       # Project card, project header, etc.
├── pages/             # Route-level page components
├── hooks/             # Custom React hooks
├── services/          # API call functions
├── stores/            # Zustand stores
├── utils/             # Pure utility functions
└── constants/         # App-wide constants
```

### Component Rules
- Functional components only — no class components
- One component per file
- File named same as component: `VoiceCheckoff.jsx`
- Props destructured at top of function
- No inline styles — Tailwind classes only
- If a component exceeds ~150 lines, split it

### Tailwind Rules
- Use design tokens via CSS variables defined in `index.css`
- Always use these semantic colors (not raw Tailwind colors):
  - Primary: `bg-blue-600` (`#2563EB`)
  - Navy: `bg-slate-900` (`#0F172A`)
  - Success: `bg-green-600`
  - AI accent: `bg-violet-600` / `border-violet-500`
  - Warning: `bg-yellow-400`
- Touch targets: minimum `h-12 w-12` (48px) for all interactive elements
- Text minimum: `text-base` (16px) on mobile
- Never use `text-xs` for anything the user needs to read

### Mobile-First Rules
- All layouts start mobile, then add `md:` and `lg:` breakpoints
- Primary actions in bottom 1/3 of screen (thumb reach zone)
- Use bottom sheets (slide up from bottom) not modals for overlays
- Checklist items: full-width tap targets, min height `h-14`
- Avoid horizontal scrolling

### AI UI Rules
- AI features always marked with ✦ sparkle icon and violet accent color
- Loading states: use skeleton screens + "Analyzing..." text, not just spinners
- Confidence feedback: show visually (color or icon) but not as a raw number to users
- Always show what the AI matched BEFORE committing the action
- Every AI action must have a clear "Cancel" or "That's wrong" escape

### State Management
- Server state (API data): React Query only — no manual fetch in useEffect
- UI state (modals, tabs, toggles): local useState
- Cross-component UI state: Zustand store
- Never store API data in Zustand — that's React Query's job

### Error Handling
- Every API call must handle: loading, error, empty, success states
- Network errors: show toast with retry option
- AI failures: gracefully fall back to manual selection
- Use React Error Boundaries around AI components

---

## SHARED CONVENTIONS

### Naming
- Files: `kebab-case` for React files, `snake_case` for Ruby files
- Variables/functions: `camelCase` in JS, `snake_case` in Ruby
- Constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` in both
- Database columns: `snake_case` always
- API JSON keys: `camelCase` (Rails serializer should convert)

### Git Commits
Follow conventional commits:
```
feat: add voice check-off flow
fix: correct confidence threshold for photo match
chore: add RSpec tests for VoiceMatchService
refactor: extract AI prompts into constants
```

### Environment Variables
Backend (`.env`):
```
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=
OPENAI_API_KEY=
AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
AWS_BUCKET=
DATABASE_URL=
```

Frontend (`.env`):
```
VITE_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:3000
```

Never commit API keys. Never hardcode secrets. Always use env vars.

---

## AI PROMPT STANDARDS

### Voice Match Prompt Template
```
You are a job site assistant helping a contractor check off tasks.
The contractor just said: "{transcription}"
Here are the incomplete checklist items:
{items_as_numbered_list}

Return ONLY valid JSON, no other text:
{
  "matched_item_id": "<id or null>",
  "confidence": <0.0-1.0>,
  "reasoning": "<one sentence>"
}

Match loosely — contractors speak casually. Partial matches count.
```

### Photo Match Prompt Template
```
You are a job site assistant. Look at this photo from a job site.
Determine which of these checklist items it most likely documents:
{items_as_numbered_list}

Return ONLY valid JSON, no other text:
{
  "matched_item_id": "<id or null>",
  "confidence": <0.0-1.0>,
  "description": "<one sentence: what you see>",
  "reasoning": "<why this matches>"
}
```

### Q&A Prompt Template
```
You are a helpful job site assistant for a contractor.
Project: {project_name} | Trade: {trade_type}
Checklist: {checklist_name}
Items: {items_with_status_timestamps}

Question: "{user_question}"

Answer in 1-2 sentences. Be direct and practical. No filler words.
For "what's next?" return ONLY the item name.
```

---

## CONFIDENCE THRESHOLD CONSTANTS

```javascript
// src/constants/ai.js
export const AI_CONFIDENCE = {
  AUTO_SUGGEST: 0.90,    // Auto-suggest, 2s countdown
  SUGGEST: 0.70,         // Show suggestion, require tap
  GUESS: 0.50,           // Show as guess, ask "is this right?"
  NO_MATCH: 0.49         // No suggestion, show full list
}
```

```ruby
# app/constants/ai_constants.rb
module AiConstants
  AUTO_SUGGEST_THRESHOLD = 0.90
  SUGGEST_THRESHOLD      = 0.70
  GUESS_THRESHOLD        = 0.50
end
```

---

## WHAT NOT TO DO

- ❌ Don't call Claude or Whisper APIs from the React frontend — always go through Rails
- ❌ Don't use modals on mobile — use bottom sheets
- ❌ Don't use text smaller than 16px (text-base) for readable content
- ❌ Don't put logic in Rails controllers — use service objects
- ❌ Don't store server data in Zustand — use React Query
- ❌ Don't auto-complete a checklist item without user confirmation
- ❌ Don't show raw confidence scores (like "87.3%") to users — use visual cues instead
- ❌ Don't build any feature that requires two hands to operate
- ❌ Don't skip the offline queue — contractors lose signal constantly
- ❌ Don't hardcode checklist items — everything comes from templates or user input
